[normal]1.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Royal Mail is pleased to respond to the Select Committee for Business, Innovation and Skills on its short inquiry into 
[normal]the 
[normal]Government’s 
[normal]intention to conduct a sale of shares in Royal Mail
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]The Government’s intention
[normal] is to dispose of a majority stake, taking into account shares sold and those transferred to employees as part of the employee share scheme.
[normal] 
[normal]The Government will retain flexibility around the size of stake to be sold, as this will be influenced by market co
[normal]nditions at the time of the transaction, investor demand and the objective to ensure that overall value for money for the taxpayer is achieved. 
[normal]Royal Mail welcome
[normal]s the Government’s
[normal] decision. The company needs to be 
[normal]flexible, responsive,
[normal] 
[normal]and have future acc
[normal]ess to 
[normal]capital.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Royal Mail is also pleased that
[normal] the Government has decided to allocate 10% of the
[normal] shares
[normal] in
[normal] the company to
[normal] all eligible employees
[normal] free of charge. Employees of the Group will have a real stake in the company and a significant voice
[normal] in its future
[normal].
[normal] This is the largest 
[normal]free stake of any major UK privatisation
[normal].
[normal] More employees will be able to participate in the
[normal] Royal Mail
[normal] Free Share scheme than in any other UK privatisation for almost 30 years.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Royal Mail is the sole provider of the 
[normal]Universal
[normal] Postal
[normal] Service in the UK, serving more than 29 million addresses, 6 days a week. Our Universal Service obligations are outlined in th
[normal]e Postal Services Act 2011. They are 
[normal]set out in detail in the Universal Service Order. This statutory document is
[normal] set and regulated by the 
[normal]communications regulator Ofcom
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]As the Universal Service provider, Royal Mail has a legal obligation to provide a uniform-priced Universal Service across the UK
[normal], including remote and rural areas
[normal]. 
[normal]W
[normal]e
[normal] maintain a 
[normal]substantial 
[normal]network
[normal] across the UK – a network with the ability to deliver to every household and collect from every collection point, six days a week
[normal].
[normal]  Any change to this obligation would require an affirmative vote in both Houses of Parliament.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1.5
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Post Office Ltd has been 
[normal]formally separated from Royal Mail Group since April 201
[normal]2
[normal]. We
[normal] continue
[normal] as sister companie
[normal]s
[normal] with 
[normal]substantial
[normal] shared interests
[normal]. Post Office 
[normal]is an important retail outlet for
[normal] Royal Mail services under a long term commercial 
[normal]distribution 
[normal]agreement.
[normal] The mutual 
[normal]commercial success of both companies is best served by Royal Mail and Post Office working closely together for the benefit of 
[normal]customers. 
[normal]A successful, com
[normal]mercially viable Royal Mail can
[normal] generate more business for the Post Office and help secure its nationw
[normal]ide network of branches.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]2.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In December 2008, Richard Hooper published an independent report into
[normal] the UK postal services sector. His report 
[normal]outlined steps to make 
[normal]the Universal Service sustainable. Hooper made four 
[normal]key 
[normal]policy recommendations:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]2.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Hooper made clear that his “recommendations are a package…Each element of the package is needed if the universal service is to be sustained.”
[normal] 
[normal]Hooper updated his review in the sum
[normal]mer of 2010. His update argued that “private sector capital would inject private sector disciplines into the company and would reduce the risk of political intervention in commercial decisions, thus accelerating modernisation.” Hooper also considered alter
[normal]native not-for-profit and not-for-dividend models, but concluded that these would not be 
[normal]“
[normal]appropriate or workable.
[normal]”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Government facilitated 
[normal]the 
[normal]implementation of Hooper’s recommendations through the Postal Services Act 2011. 
[normal]This
[normal] allowed 
[normal]the 
[normal]transfer
[normal] of
[normal] 
[normal]the Group’s 
[normal]pension 
[normal]liabilities for pre-April 2012 service and certain pension assets relating to the Royal Mail Pension Plan
[normal],
[normal] to 
[normal]Government. The Government also 
[normal]appoint
[normal]ed
[normal] Ofcom as the new postal services regulator. Ofcom has since reformed the regulat
[normal]ory framework for postal services in the UK.
[normal] 
[normal]T
[normal]he Government aims to complete 
[normal]the 
[normal]implementation of Hooper’s package of reforms through a sale of shares in Royal Mail in this financial year.
[normal] The Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills has sai
[normal]d that “now the time has come for Government to step back from Royal Mail and allow its management to focus wholeheartedly on growing the business and planning for the future.”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Privatisa
[normal]tion will give Royal Mail flexible
[normal] access to private capital. This 
[normal]will
[normal] be a positive step for Royal Mail and the Universal Service.
[normal] Royal Mail wants to combine the best of the public and private sectors.
[normal] 
[normal]For Royal Mail to innovate and 
[normal]remain competitive in the marketplace
[normal],
[normal] it
[normal] need
[normal]s to continue its
[normal] transformation. 
[normal]Deutsch
[normal]e Post has invested more than £20bn in its business since it was floated in 2001 whilst delivering one of the highest quality universal services in Europe. In comparison, since Royal Mail began its modernisation programme in 2006/7, it has invested c.£2.8b
[normal]n on modernisation. 
[normal]Royal Mail needs to increase revenue from the growing parcels market. This is 
[normal]a 
[normal]competitive
[normal] market
[normal] and investment in new technology will be crucial. 
[normal]Having 
[normal]flexible
[normal] 
[normal]access to 
[normal]capital would help to deliver our long term strategy, leading
[normal] to a sustainable Universal Service.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The Universal Service[bold]&#xa0;[bold]3.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Royal Mail is the designated provider of the universal postal service, committed to providing the high quality U
[normal]niversal 
[normal]S
[normal]ervice
[normal] that the Government
[normal] and regulator have
[normal] set down. We ar
[normal]e honoured to provide the universal service.
[normal] Royal Mail Group’s strategic vision is to be recognised as the best delivery company in the UK.
[normal] We believe that the nationwide network we maintain in order to deliver the Universal Service puts us in a strong position to compete and meet emerging customer demand. 
[normal]T
[normal]he ability to visit every address in the UK, six days a week
[normal] provides commercial advan
[normal]tages to Royal Mail
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Postal Services Act 2011 protects the high-quality Universal Service
[normal] enjoyed by customers across the UK
[normal]. Its protections would continue to apply following any sale of shares
[normal] in Royal Mail
[normal]. The protections include a uniform service
[normal] to rural areas, to which Royal Mail must continue to deliver the same high-quality service or risk large fines.  It also protects specific services, such as the Articles for the Blind scheme, which provides free postal services to blind or partially sight
[normal]ed people.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Postal Services Act 2011 sets down the minimum requirements of the universal postal service in law. These minimum requirements include the collection of letters every Monday to Saturday and a delivery service at affordable prices in accorda
[normal]nce with a uniform tariff throughout the UK.  The requirements are set out 
[normal]in S
[normal]ection 31 of the Postal Services Act 2011.  Any change to these minimum requirements would require the approval of both houses of the UK Parliament. The requirements are:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Universal Service requirement[bold]Applies [bold]after privatisation[bold]6 day a week delivery to the home or premises of every individual in the UK
[normal]Yes
[normal]6 day a week collection from every access point (e.g. post boxes and post offices) in the UK
[normal]Yes
[normal]A uniform, 
[normal]affordable tariff across the UK
[normal]Yes
[normal]The provision of a registered items service at a uniform tariff
[normal]Yes
[normal]The provision of an insured items service at a uniform tariff
[normal]Yes
[normal]Free postage for the blind and partially sighted
[normal]Yes
[normal]A free service of conveying 
[normal]qualifying legislative petitions
[normal]Yes
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]First and Second Class stamped and franked mail, and Royal Mail First and Second Class parcels to 20kg, are part of the Universal Service.  That means they have to be offered on a universal (“one-price-goes-anywhere”) tariff at affordable prices.  Ofcom ha
[normal]ve recently concluded that these services meet the needs of the vast majority of postal users and there is no case for changing the terms of the Universal Service (Ofcom Review of postal users’ needs, 27 March 2013). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Prices[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]3.5
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In 2012, Ofcom said that Roya
[normal]l Mail’s fi
[normal]nancial position meant there was
[normal] 
[normal]“
[normal]a risk to the financial sustainability of the Universal Service”. Ofcom recognised the need for Royal Mail “to materially increase prices in order to support the sustainability of the universal service.” 
[normal]Royal 
[normal]Mail increased stamp prices in April 2012 to help to address the threat to the sustainability of the Universal Service.
[normal] Royal Mail also reconfigured its parcels tariffs in 2013
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.6
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Stamp prices, whether set under public or private ownership, are subject to 
[normal]significant competitive pressures. Customers have many alternatives to the post. 
[normal]Ofcom have reported that more than 
[normal]37 billion te
[normal]x
[normal]t messages were sent in 2012
[normal]. 
[normal]More than half of adults own a smart phone, 
[normal]and 49% regularly use smart phones to access the int
[normal]ernet
[normal] [Ofcom Communication Markets Report, August 2013]
[normal]. 
[normal]Households and businesses increasingly use e-mail to communicate in preference to post. 
[normal]These are just a few examples of the proliferation of alternatives to the post, which naturally mean that Royal
[normal] Mail must be cautious in its pricing and customer strategies.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.7
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]UK stamp prices are among the best value in the EU. In five of the six weight steps for First Class and Second Class mail, the cost of UK stamps are ranked in the bottom half of prices when 
[normal]compared with other EU countries. In some cases, the UK is the cheapest.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.8
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Ofcom is legally obliged to ensure an affordable postal service and can reintroduce regulation on any Universal Service product. Ofcom concluded in March 2013 that Royal Mail’s servi
[normal]ces were affordable to consumers and small and medium sized businesses.
[normal] Ofcom said (in their report on the affordability of postal services, published 19 March 2013):
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“The evidence we have collected indicates that universal postal services are affordable 
[normal]for both residential consumers (including low income and other vulnerable consumers) and businesses (including small and medium businesses) at current prices. We have reviewed the price changes that are due to take effect from 2 April 2013 (as announced by
[normal] Royal Mail in March 2013), and consider that universal postal services will continue to be affordable following these changes.”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.9
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In 2013 there was no increase in the price of first class or second class stamps for letters. Ofcom has also set safeguard pri
[normal]ce caps on Second Class stamped mail in 2012, which also covers Second Class parcels up to 2kg. The cap
[normal] calculation
[normal] is set for seven years (from April 2012). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Quality of service[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]3.10
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Royal Mail is regulated by Ofcom.  The regulator sets a minimum delivery 
[normal]standard for the whole of the UK.  Currently the target for First Class mail is 93% delivery the next working day.  For Second Class mail the target is 98.5% delivery within three working days. Royal Mail has amongst the highest service specifications of a
[normal]ny major EU member
[normal] state. These
[normal] include:
