[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.11
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Royal Mail’s Quality of Service report for 2012/13 reveals that the vast majority of mail was delivered in 
[normal]line with its targets. Royal Mail narrowly missed the 93.0 per 
[normal]cent First Class mail target with 92.4 per cent of this mail delivered the next working day, when taking into account disruption from external events.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.12
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In a very competitive market, Quality of Service is one of the key drivers of success. That would not change if Royal Mail were 
[normal]privatised
[normal]. The Quality of Service regime that applies to Royal Mail under public ownership will continue to apply under private
[normal] ownership - Ofcom has specified the minimum standards un
[normal]der the Universal Service Order
[normal].
[normal] We are the only postal operator in the UK who has to meet these high standards and regularly publish performance results.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.13
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Evidence from elsewhere in Europe shows tha
[normal]t postal operators maintain or improve their quality of service following privatisation.
[normal] Both Deutsche Post and Austria
[normal] Post deliver more than 95% of letters the day after posting. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]4.1
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Over the past decade, the postal services sector has changed 
[normal]dramatically
[normal].
[normal] A decline in mail volumes has coincided with the liberalisation of the market and the emergence of competition. In recent
[normal] years, we have seen a significant
[normal] increase in the number of parcels being sent. All of this has meant a difficult proces
[normal]s of change for our people. Many of Royal Mail’s employees have seen changes to their working practices as the company 
[normal]has adapted its operations
[normal] to the changed mix of mail. 
[normal]More than 50,000 people have left the business since March 2003.
[normal] 
[normal]Change will conti
[normal]nue and the company will 
[normal]employ fewer people in the future,
[normal] whoever owns it. The company remains committed to the overarching objective of achieving this without compulsory redundancies.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.2
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Royal Mail Group
[normal]’s
[normal] vision 
[normal]is 
[normal]to be 
[normal]recognised as 
[normal]the most successful
[normal] delivery company in the UK. Our strategy is underpinned by three priorities: capitalising on growth in online retailing to grow our parcels businesses; continuing to m
[normal]anage
[normal] structural decline in the letters market by maximising the value of mail; and by being customer-focused. We believe we can drive sustainable, profitable growth that will enable us to obtain ongoing access to external capital and secure a sustainable futur
[normal]e for our Company. 
[normal]The company will need to be smaller and more efficient in the future regardless of ownership.
[normal] Delivering this strategy will require significant change. We will consult on any changes with the CWU, Unite, and our people.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Employee terms a[bold]nd conditions[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]All terms and conditions and collective agreements that apply to employees would remain in place were there to be a change in ownership of the company, on the same basis that they apply to employees now. Royal Mail will continue to have a pr
[normal]edominantly full time workforce, supported by part time workers, with a national split of around 75% full time workers to 25% part time. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.4
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]These 
[normal]job security
[normal], and other, commitments are part of current agreements with the Communication Workers Union. If 
[normal]and when any changes are proposed, Royal Mail will, as now,
[normal] 
[normal]and where appropriate, discuss these with the unions with a view to reaching agreement.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.5
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We have proposed a three year agreement with the CWU, protecting terms and conditions and committing to sig
[normal]nificant pay rises
[normal] for employees in the core business
[normal]. The agreement would include a pay increase of 8.6% over the three year period. This is highly competitive, and is believed to be one of the best pay deals on offer from any major UK company at this tim
[normal]e.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.6
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Royal Mail is 
[normal]also 
[normal]seeking to create a legally binding and enforceable contract with the CWU. The proposed contract would mean pay and protections for employees could not be changed for the three-year period of the contract without CWU agreement. Royal
[normal] Mail believes 
[normal]that this has not been done before for any major 
[normal]UK 
[normal]privatisation
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.7
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]In addition, as part of the proposed agreement, Royal Mail is committed to provide and enhance existing services to customers using the current workforce and there will be n
[normal]o change to the current structure of 
[normal]the 
[normal]company in relation to these services.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] No additional outsourcing of services is expected during the period of the agreement.
