[normal]4.9
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Royal Mail welcomes the Government’s decision on free share allocation. Eligible employees will automatically have a meaningful stake in the company and the potential to benefit from its future success. 
[normal]Academic studies have shown that 
[normal]most
[normal] UK employees who engaged with their employee share ownership plan were more motivated and committed to their employer
[normal], and many
[normal] 
[normal]felt that participating in an ESO gave them a greater sense of personal ownership for their job or a greater sense of personal ownership for the company. 
[normal](
[normal]Loughborough University four-year study into the human impact of HMRC-approved all-employee share pla
[normal]ns, 2012).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.10
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Shares will be allocated 
[normal]to all eligible staff equally, reg
[normal]ardless of grade or pay levels
[normal]. The allocation will be pro-rated based on an employee’s paid hours to differentiate between full and part time workers. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.11
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Employees will be able to see t
[normal]he value of their shares any time that the stock market is open. They will also be able to vote in key decisions on how the company is run. The company will use this opportunity to engage
[normal] with employees even more, as well as actively communicating the bene
[normal]fits of free shares
[normal]. We will conduct major internal communications programmes around the company’s results and commercial strategy. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.12
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The overwhelming majority of Royal Mail Group employees in the UK, including employees working in Parcelforce Worldwide, 
[normal]will be eligible for free shares if they meet certain criteria. Employees of GLS and other subsidiaries and joint ventures are not eligible to receive free shares.
[normal] 
[normal]The free employee shares will be of the same class as those available for wider sale. 
[normal]Employ
[normal]ees will therefore obtain voting rights and will be eligible to receive dividends like other shareholders. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.13
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Royal Mail employees who are eligible for an automatic free share allocation under the employee share scheme will also have the option to buy addit
[normal]ional shares through the
[normal] Employee Priority Offer
[normal]. Eligible employees will be given priority when those shares are allocated. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.14
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The free shares to be offered on a flotation are not related to section 31 of the Growth and Infrastructure Act 2013. The free sh
[normal]ares are to be awarded under the long-standing, HMRC approved share plan known as a Share Incentive Plan. Further details have yet to be announced but, under HMRC rules, employees cannot be asked to pay anything or give anything up, including employment ri
[normal]ghts, to receive free shares.
[normal] 
[normal]Royal Mail will write to all employees nearer the time of the issue. Employees will be given the option to opt-out of the employee share offer if they do not wish to participate for any reason.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Working with our unions[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]4.15
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Working together with our colleagues and unions
[normal] is
[normal] the best way to be successful. We work together with both the CWU and Unite on a range of issues, including reform of the regulatory regime, 
[normal]new ways of working, our Agenda for Growth, 
[normal]workplace safety, an
[normal]d the issue of dangerous dogs. 
[normal]Whilst we do not agree on everything, we value the input our unions give us and the work that they conduct throughout the business. We will continue to 
[normal]work closely
[normal] with our union colleagues during the on
[normal]-
[normal]going transformation
[normal] of the company.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.16
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Royal Mail is currently negotiating a legally binding agreement on pay, terms and conditions for employees. 
[normal]The CWU have said that they will ballot for industrial action should 
[normal]progress not be made by September 2013
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.17
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Even the suggestion
[normal] of industrial action is not
[normal] in the best interests of the company, its customers, or its employees. Royal Mail’s revenue is increasingly 
[normal]generated by
[normal] parcels – 48% of total revenue in 2012-13. This is a very competitive sector. Our customers have many choi
[normal]ces and can easily switch their business to competitors.
[normal] 
[normal]Any disruption to our service is not helpful.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Pensions[bold]&#xa0;[bold]4.18
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Royal Mail’s main pension plan – the Royal Mail Pension Plan
[normal] (RMPP)
[normal] – was closed to new members in March 2008. At the same time, members
[normal]’ benefits ceased to build up on a final salary basis and switched to Career Salary Defined Benefit. Despite these changes, the Plan remained one of the largest defined benefit schemes in the UK (based on membership and assets). 
[normal]The company made s
[normal]ignifican
[normal]t pension deficit cash contributions on top of its ongoing pension costs
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]It
[normal] recognised a deficit on its balance sheet which ranged from £2.7bn to £7.5bn. This meant Royal Mail faced issues with respect to Going Concern, it was balance sheet insolvent and 
[normal]it carried material pension risk and volatility.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.19
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The European Commission granted State Aid approval on 21 March 2012, allowing the transfer of almost all of the pension liabilities and assets of RMPP built up until 31 March 2012 to be transferred to Gover
[normal]nment. The transfer left RMPP fully funded on an actuarial basis at the time of the transfer, and immediately removed the requirement for the company to make further deficit cash contributions. 
